  "dateModified": "2026-01-01",
  "datePublished": "2026-01-01",
  "description": "Food-safe describes a material, surface, or substance that is suitable for contact with food without introducing harmful chemicals, residues, or contaminants. In home gardening — particularly when growing sprouts and microgreens — the food-safe status of containers, growing media, and cleaning agents determines whether the harvest is safe to eat.\nCommon food-safe considerations for home growers include: whether a plastic container is rated for food contact (look for recycling codes 1, 2, 4, or 5 and explicit food-grade labeling), whether a growing medium contains fertilizers or treatments not approved for edible crops, and whether cleaning products leave residues that could transfer to sprouts during the rinse cycle. Glass jars and stainless steel mesh are generally food-safe by default; plastics and coated metals require verification.\n",
  "name": "food-safe",
